body:
#### Issue details
If mote HTTP requests are invoked in same time above the maximal allowed network thread count (specified by the configuration option `maxNetThread`) then they are rejected. The configuration option is useless because of this.

The reason for this is that the `NetJavaImpl` creates a `ThreadPoolExecutor` with work queue set to `SynchronousQueue` instance. The `SynchronousQueue` offer method always rejects an item, thus if active count is higher then maximal thread pool size (set by `maxNetThread`) the task is not accepted (`ThreadPoolExecutor#execute` throws `LinkedBlockingQueue`).

#### Reproduction steps/code
```java
// config settings
config.maxNetThreads = 5;

// Listener
class MyHttpResponseListener implements Net.HttpResponseListener {
  void handleHttpResponse (HttpResponse httpResponse) {}
  void failed (Throwable t) {
    System.out.println("failed: " + t.getMessage());
  }
  void cancelled () {}
}

// create more then 5 HTTP requests
for (int i = 0; i < 6; i++) {
  HttpRequest httpRequest = /* ... */;
  Gdx.net.sendHttpRequest(httpRequest, null); // the sixth request will print message `failed: ...`
}
```

#### Version of LibGDX and/or relevant dependencies
_1.9.14_

#### Stacktrace
For  `maxNetThread` set to 5:
```java
Task java.util.concurrent.FutureTask@34f07602 rejected from java.util.concurrent.ThreadPoolExecutor@49035613[Running, pool size = 5, active threads = 5, queued tasks = 0, completed tasks = 0]
```

#### Please select the affected platforms
- [x] Android
- [x] iOS
- [ ] HTML/GWT
- [x] Windows
- [x] Linux
- [x] MacOS
